DENGUE VIRUSES, TRANSMISSION BY _AEDES ALBOPICTUS_ (04)
*******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Dengue viruses, transm. by _Ae. albopictus_ 980425215206
Dengue viruses, transm. by _Ae. albopictus_(02) 980428001011
Dengue viruses, transm. by _Ae. albopictus_(03) 980504220836
Date: Tue, 05 May 1998 08:20:18 -0600
From: Walter J. Tabachnick <Tabachni@uwyo.edu>

Rural outbreaks of dengue occurred in Asia prior to the introduction of
_Aedes aegypti_. C.E.G. Smith (Am. J. Trop. Med. Hyg. 59:3-11. 1956)
provided an excellent review of the history of dengue in Asia. The vector
of the rural epidemics was likely _Ae. albopictus_, a rural vector of the
dengue viruses and native to the region. Urban dengue epidemics were not
known to occur in Asia until the latter half of the nineteenth century.
Smith attributes this to the arrival of the only vector capable of urban
endemicity, _Ae. aegypti_. A more detailed discussion of the evolution of
_Ae. aegypti_ can be found in Tabachnick, W.J., Amer. Entomol. 37:14-24. 1991.
--
Walter J. Tabachnick, Ph.D.
